The Tinellbian Languages Dictionary

  • Random Entry

The Tinellbian Languages Dictionary

About

This dictionary aims to describe all the vocabulary items of the twenty Tinellbian languages, consisting of High Lulani and its descendants. In addition, miscellaneous English neologisms have been added, including proper nouns.

Searching

The search box at the bottom of each page allows one to proceed directly to any dictionary entry. Contrariwise, the search box in the navigation pane runs a general search of the site.

Sa’imi

High Lulani

さいみ

/saˈʔimɨ/

proper derived noun

Caemi; goddess of light, energy and chaos; light-giver

Notes

Also the name given to the personification of the Nuobi sun.

Etymology

sa’i さい light + -mi み giver

    -a

    High Lulani

    、あ

    /ə/

    derivational suffix ( noun / verb → interjection )

    interjection marker; inj

    Examples

      • mica みや hello
      • hacca はっや good morning
      • nara なら good night
      • hira ひら please
      • kica きや pardon?

    -aku

    High Lulani

    、あく

    /əkʰʉ/

    derivational suffix (noun → noun)

    augmentative

    Examples

      • tissaku てっさく gale
      • ’isilaku いせわく depression

    High Lulani

    、あら・

    /aɽ/

    terminative; trm

    Derived Terms

    dynamic: qixara ねざら

    stative: pari ぱり

    negative: qilaru ねわる

    habitual: takaru たかる

    gnomic: rusara るさら

    present:

    future:

    gnomic: rukaru るかる

    See also: ba

    High Lulani

    ば

    /bə/

    derivational suffix (verb → noun)

    derives an animate agentive noun from a verb

    Examples

      • ’ussaba うっさば follower
      • caba やば helper
      • hisuba ひすば administrator

    -ca

    High Lulani

    や

    /cʰa/

    determiner

    only

    Examples

    ʔusuca jannimufa mica.

    。うすや ぢっにむへ みや。

    ’usu-ca jannimufa mica.

    1int-only dance allowed

    “Only I may dance.”

    See Also

      • -nisa にさ sole

    -cama

    High Lulani

    やま

    /ˈcʰamə/

    determiner

    usual; old; familiar; customary

    -cari

    High Lulani

    やり

    /ˈcaɽɨ/

    determiner

    remaining; rest

    Examples

      • musacari むさやり rest of the day

    -ci

    High Lulani

    ち

    /ci/ · /cɨ/

    derivational nominalisation suffix (verb → noun)

    creates an abstract noun from an adjectival or chromatic verb

    Notes

    This suffix is used to derive the names of colours from their respective verbs

    Derived Terms

      • kiʔaci きっあち white
      • namaci なまち weakness

    -du

    High Lulani

    ど

    /dʉ/

    derivational suffix (verb → noun)

    derives an inanimate patientive noun from a verb

    Examples

      • dasidu だせど food
      • kassudu かっすど trade goods
      • maladu まわど reflection

    -ffi

    High Lulani

    っべ

    /fːɨ/

    derivational suffix (verb → noun)

    instrument; tool

    Examples

      • sikuffi せくっべ spear
      • dasiffi だせっべ cutlery

    -fi

    High Lulani

    べ

    /fɨ/

    suffix (noun → noun)

    honoured; exalted; sacred

    Examples

      • lulanifi をわにべ honoured queen
      • faʔafi へっあべ sacred language
      • sunufi すぬべ robe

    -fi’atu

    High Lulani

    べあと

    /fɨʔatʰʉ/

    derived determiner

    certain; particular

    Etymology

    fi’a べあ individuality + -tu と drv

    -fu

    High Lulani

    ふ

    /fʉ/

    pronoun suffix

    and you

    Notes

    Forms first person inclusive plural pronouns when applied to first person pronouns.

    See Also

      • -pa ぱ and them

      • dative: pixifu ぴしふ
      • alienable genitive: pagufu ぱぐふ

    third person inclusive:

      • intransitive: ’usufupa うすふぱ
      • transitive: sumafupa すまふぱ
      • ablative: puttufupa ぷっとふぱ

    High Lulani

    っは

    /çːə/

    mathematics derivational suffix (numeral)

    ten

    Etymology

    From the final two morae of qihha ねっは zero

    -hita

    High Lulani

    ひた

    /ˌhitʰə/

    determiner

    opposite; antonym

    Examples

      • jami-hita ぢみひた evidence of non-existence
      • dumi-hita どみひた attempt to avoid

    -hu

    High Lulani

    ほ

    /hʉ/

    derivational suffix (abstract noun → noun)

    denotes something with a sense of moving outwards

    Examples

      • tajihu たじほ magic power
      • qarihu げりほ sorry
      • lannuhu わっぬほ stomach

    -illu

    High Lulani

    、いっを

    /ˌiʎːʉ/

    derivational suffix (verb)

    passive

    -ilu

    High Lulani

    、いを

    /ɨlʉ/

    inflectional suffix (verb)

    passive; psv

    Notes

    This suffix is attached to verbs ending with a geminate consonant.

    -ini

    High Lulani

    、いに

    /ɨnɨ/

    derivational cisclass suffix (noun / verb)

    diminutive; derives a term of lesser intensity or size from another term; dim

    Notes

    Obscene when added to a noun referring to a person.

    Examples

      • ’ahatini あはてに contentment
      • tissini てっせに breeze
      • ranini らにに chips
      • bi’ini びいに to itch

    -ja

    High Lulani

    ぢ

    /ɟə/

    derivational suffix (noun: inanimate → abstract)

    derives an abstract noun from an inanimate noun

    Examples

      • ru’ihaja るいはぢ history

    -ji’a

    High Lulani

    じあ

    /ˌɟiʔə/

    determiner

    not; not a

    Examples

      • takaji’a たかじあ not a sound

    -ka

    High Lulani

    か

    /kə/

    inflectional suffix (verb)

    make; abv

    Notes

    Used after verbs with geminate final consonants.

    See Also

      • -kka 、っか abv

    bitta

    High Lulani

    びった

    /ˈbitːə/

    inanimate noun

    time

    Definition

    the two temporal dimensions

    Notes

    The first dimension of time is subjective: a person’s birth is before their death.

    The second dimension is objective: if one time-travels into the past, then one’s death may well be upstream of one’s birth.

    Derived Terms

      • jannibitta ぢっにびった to time travel

    Hypernyms

      • calu やを dimension

    See Also

      • ’u’ili ういえ reality
      • sufi すべ space
      • maʔu まっう gingla

    bunali

    High Lulani

    ぶなえ

    /bʉˈnalɨ/

    derived abstract noun

    rhyme; assonance

    Definition

    to have the same vowels and placement of geminates

    Examples

    (These are perhaps nonsense words, to demonstrate bunali)

      • papa / para
      • kana / lara
      • biru / kitu
      • kippu / lirru

    Non-examples

      • biru / baru - different vowel sound
      • kiru / kirru - different geminate placement

    Etymology

    buna ぶな homophone + -li え quasi-

    High Lulani

    /ˈcalʉ/

    dimension

    Definition

    2. One of four ways in which something can be measured

    。きべ やを ら あぬ さはき。

    “Two cubed is eight.”

    dissu

    High Lulani

    でっす

    /ˈdisːʉ/

    ambitransitive perceptive verb

    to feel

    Notes

    Used for emotions and loves, often compounded. Such compounds tend to be adjectival verbs.

    Examples

    ʔusu sacu dissu ’ahati.

    。うす さゆ でっす あはて。

    1int 2abl feel happiness.

    ’usu sacu dissu ’ahati.

    “You make me happy.”

    Derived Terms

      • dissu’ahati でっすあはて to be happy
      • dissu’isili でっすいせえ to be sad
      • dissu’ulanu でっすうわぬ to be aroused
      • dissutihura でっすてほら to be astonished
      • dissumalliju でっすまっえよ to be happy
      • dissumici でっすみち to feel peace
      • diss·sutti でっすすって to be afraid
      • diss·samma でっすさっま to feel romantic

    abstract noun

    youth; newness

    Derived Terms

      • dissuri でっすり stranger
      • diss·sa でっすさ young person
      • dissudanagi でっすだなぎ pardon
      • padissu ぱでっす to learn

    dumi

    High Lulani

    どみ

    /ˈdumɨ/

    abstract noun ~ modal occasion adverb

    nighttime hours; night; evening

    Antonym

      • musa むさ daylight

    abstract noun ~ purpose adverb

    attempt; try to

    Notes

    Does not imply anything about success or failure.

    When used with ablative promotion, gives nuance of encouraged.

    Examples

    Quhu kupaji dasikka mihu dumi.

    。もほくぱじだせっかみほどみ。

    quhu ku-paji dasi-kka mihu dumi.

    3ani;tra dat-fruit eat-abv 3ani;int try.

    “She encouraged him to eat fruit.”

    hussudiccaha

    nufira

    High Lulani

    ぬべら

    /nʉfiɽə/

    inanimate derived compound noun ~ modal adverb

    want; desire; want to

    Notes

    When used adverbially, this word tends to only be used in first person, or second person questions.

    Examples

    ʔusu ra’u dihuri nufira.

    。うすらうでほりぬべら。

    ʔusu ra’u di-huri nufira.

    1int prs;sta down-sea want.

    “I want to be under the sea.”

    Etymology

    nu ぬ desire + fira べら wish

    tali

    High Lulani

    たえ

    /ˈtʰalɨ/

    transitive motive dative verb

    to take away from someone

    Examples

    ʔaggami pi kalutuhhisa tali

    ’ita’i.

    。あっがみ ぴ かをとっひさ たえ いたい。

    ’aggami pi kalu-tuhhisa tali ’ita’i.

    Police_officer pst;sta abl-farmer take car.

    “The police officer took the car from the farmer.”

    mathematics particle

    subtract; minus

    Examples

    Qihha tali bila ’anu kifi.

    。ねっは たえ びわ あぬ きべ。

    qihha tali bila ’anu kifi.

    Zero take ree equal three.

    “Zero subtract minus three equals three.”

    tana

    High Lulani

    たな

    /ˈtʰanə/

    abstract noun

    there is; what there is

    Examples

    Tana ru lulani.

    。たな る をわに。

    tana ru lulani.

    there_is prs;gno queen.

    “There is a queen (in existence).”

    Notes

    while this is not a noun in the strict sense of the word, it does act like one when used by itself as a subject. This noun can be used as the base to nominalise adpositions.

    Examples

      • tanadi たなで what is above
      • tanajimuli たなじむえ what is outside

    See Also

      • malu まを there is

    xu

    High Lulani

    ず

    /ɕu/

    transitive apparent verb

    to put out; to radiate; to broadcast

    Notes

    Inanimate themes are objects, animate themes use ka

    Examples

    Filli pixi xusina.

    。べっえ ぴし ずせな。

    filli pixi xu-sina.

    2int 1dat seem-beauty.

    “You seem pretty to me.”

    Filli ka’aggami xu.

    。べっえ かあっがみず。

    filli ka-’aggami xu.

    2int as-policeman.

    “You look like a policeman.”

    Notes

    Used for physical themes. Cf: xi し seem

    Derived Terms

      • xulagi ずわぎ to scream
      • xusina ずせな to be pretty

    inanimate noun element

    carbon

    Derived Terms

      • xusahaki lasakifi ずさはき わさきべ octane

      • ← kuxxu くっず boron

    ’ala

    High Lulani

    あわ

    /ˈʔalə/

    inanimate mass noun

    heat

    Derived Terms

      • ’alamusa あわむさ sun’s heat
      • ’alaxuhha あわずっは heat of the fire
      • puci’ala ぷちあわ summer
      • naffi’ala なっべあわ spring
      • japa’ala ぢぱあわ haze
      • cussi’ala ゆっせあわ to feel hot

    Notes

    these are just about the only terms of this type. Anything else uses the genitive.

    Examples

      • daqa ’ala
      • だげ あわ
      • da-qa ’ala
      • water-gen heat
      • “the heat of the water”

    count abstract noun

    temperature degree

    Notes

    This temperature scale is set with 0 0 at absolute zero, and 844 444 at the triple point of water.

    In ordinary use, temperatures between 788 477 and 1012 477 are given without the hundreds place.

    Numbers in bold are in decimal, numbers in italics are in balanced sesquidecimal.

    ’i

    High Lulani

    い

    /ʔi/

    ambitransitive communicative verb

    to say; to speak; to tell

    Negative Complement

    sajja さっぢ silence

    Derived Terms

      • ’isinna いせっな to tell a story
      • ’icipu いちぷ to ask
      • ’i’issi いいっせ to sing
      • ’ibibu いびぶ to complain
      • ’idajabi いだぢび to read aloud
      • ’ifuhhanaku いふっはなく to agree
      • ’ihucu いほゆ to inform
      • ’iqaca いげや to give one’s point of view
      • ’ikahu いかほ to grunt
      • ’ilagi いわぎ to scream
      • ’iluxxa いをっざ to request
      • gufu’i ぐふい radio

    Examples

    ʔusu jusi ’i li lu’i fu ra’u.

    。うす よせ い え をい ふ らう 。

    ’usu jusi ’i li fu ra’u.

    1int 3ani;dat say com love 2tra prs;sta.

    “I told her that I love you.”

    ʔusu palu’i ’i.

    。うす ぱをい い。

    ’usu pa-lu’i ’i.

    1int towards-love speak.

    “I talked about love.”

    うっし

    ’u’ili

    High Lulani

    ういえ

    /ʔʉˈʔilɨ/

    inanimate noun

    reality

    Definition

    1. the one relative dimension
    2. one point on this axis, i.e.: a world, a reality

    Derived Terms

      • janni’u’ili ぢっにういえ to slide

    Hypernyms

      • calu やを dimension

    See Also

      • bitta びった time
      • sufi すべ space
      • maʔu まっう gingla
